00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:22.610
PROFESSOR: So good afternoon.

00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:24.160
Let's have an on-time departure.

00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:34.080
Last week, we talked about
quantum states of light.

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:37.960
So we're talking about the
photon, the quantum description

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:40.590
of the electromagnetic field.

00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:45.490
And I introduced for you the
most classical quantum state

00:00:45.490 --> 00:00:49.620
of the electromagnetic field,
namely the coherent state.

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:51.990
I don't want to go through
the formalism again,

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:55.700
but the coherent state
has a simple definition,

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:57.920
simple but subtle.

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:01.170
It's an eigenstate of the
annihilation operator,

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:04.800
and it has a complex
eigenvalue alpha.

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:06.480
And from that, you
can pretty much

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:08.930
derive everything you want to
know about coherent states.

00:01:08.930 --> 00:01:09.779
Colin.

00:01:09.779 --> 00:01:12.174
AUDIENCE: What was the
purpose of-- whoever

00:01:12.174 --> 00:01:15.207
discovered eigenstates-- what
was the purpose of trying

00:01:15.207 --> 00:01:17.292
to find the eigenvalues
of destruction?

00:01:17.292 --> 00:01:18.750
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
isn't that subtle?

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:20.100
Isn't that weird?

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:24.330
How does somebody want to
find the eigenfunctions

00:01:24.330 --> 00:01:27.050
of an annihilation operator,
because the annihilation

00:01:27.050 --> 00:01:28.790
operator is non-Hermitian?

00:01:28.790 --> 00:01:30.510
And why the
annihilation operator?

00:01:30.510 --> 00:01:32.520
Why not the creation operator?

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:34.880
Well, if you try to find the
eigenstates of the creation

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:37.030
operator, you run into problems.

00:01:37.030 --> 00:01:39.070
The eigenstates are
non-normalizable.

00:01:39.070 --> 00:01:40.630
It doesn't make any sense.

00:01:40.630 --> 00:01:44.140
So here, creation and
annihilation are not symmetric.

00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:47.230
You have to pick the
annihilation operator.

00:01:47.230 --> 00:01:49.680
Colin, my gut feeling is
that somebody found it

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:50.970
in a different way.

00:01:50.970 --> 00:01:53.540
The person who popularized
those states was [INAUDIBLE],

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:57.510
and he got amply
rewarded for that.

00:01:57.510 --> 00:02:00.760
And I think you
define coherent state

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:02.700
as some form of
superposition state.

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:05.640
Maybe people have figured out
if you take a superposition

00:02:05.640 --> 00:02:08.620
state of number states that
this has special properties,

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:12.500
that this is a minimum
uncertainty state, which

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:15.530
is as close as we can
go in quantum physics

00:02:15.530 --> 00:02:19.540
to obtain a classical
electric field.

00:02:19.540 --> 00:02:21.470
So I think maybe people
found it like that.

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:24.040
And then they say, hey, but
there is another operator

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:27.330
definition eigenstate of
the annihilation operator.

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:29.896
I'm 99 percent certain.

00:02:29.896 --> 00:02:31.270
But maybe you can
ask [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:35.720
when he comes to a CUA seminar
if he discovered coherent state

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:37.890
as eigenstates of the
annihilation operator.

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:40.234
I don't think so.

00:02:40.234 --> 00:02:40.900
Other questions?

00:02:46.170 --> 00:02:48.150
So what I want to do
is-- what the theme

00:02:48.150 --> 00:02:50.510
of the end of last
lecture and today

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:55.460
is that the coherent
state is a complex number.

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:59.190
The coherent state
has a time evolution.

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:02.150
It moves in a circle.

00:03:02.150 --> 00:03:07.000
And this is really the phasor
of the electric field associated

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:07.620
with it.

00:03:07.620 --> 00:03:11.150
So coherent state,
the alpha value

00:03:11.150 --> 00:03:14.160
is directly related
to an electric field.

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:19.240
That's why this state
is closely related

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:23.820
to the classical limit of
the electromagnetic field.

00:03:33.260 --> 00:03:36.070
We discussed some properties
of the coherent state.

00:03:36.070 --> 00:03:39.130
We looked at the
fluctuations and showed

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:42.295
that it's a
Poissonian statistic.

00:03:44.850 --> 00:03:48.530
And then we use now--
once you define something,

00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:50.360
you can use it as a tool.

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:53.570
We are now using
the coherent states

00:03:53.570 --> 00:03:56.880
to look at any
other quantum state

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:59.930
of the electromagnetic field,
any statistical operator which

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:03.830
describes photons by
forming the diagram matrix

00:04:03.830 --> 00:04:09.680
element of the statistical
operator with alpha.

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:13.200
If you just want to sort of
think about it intuitively,

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:15.525
alpha is like the
best description

00:04:15.525 --> 00:04:17.550
of an electromagnetic field.

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:20.110
So if you write
down this, we ask,

00:04:20.110 --> 00:04:23.870
What is the probability for
an arbitrary quantum state

00:04:23.870 --> 00:04:26.770
described by an arbitrary
statistical operator-- what

00:04:26.770 --> 00:04:29.180
is the probability that
the electric field is

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:32.560
alpha in the
complex description?

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.650
So that's what those
quasi-probabilities

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:38.830
are-- Q of alpha.

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:44.460
And we immediately looked
at some examples, of course,

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:46.430
of probabilities.

00:04:46.430 --> 00:04:54.290
We showed that the vacuum
state is sort of an area.

00:04:54.290 --> 00:04:55.300
It's a Gaussian.

00:04:55.300 --> 00:05:01.850
And the area is-- it's an area.

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:02.900
I don't know.

00:05:02.900 --> 00:05:07.400
I forgot the [? prefect. ?]
It's on the order of 1 or 1/2.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:10.775
We realize that
thermal states are also

00:05:10.775 --> 00:05:13.890
a Gaussian centered
at the origin.

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:18.000
But it is a much
wider distribution.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.480
So thermal states have
much more uncertainty

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:24.910
in the electric field
than the vacuum state.

00:05:24.910 --> 00:05:27.410
And then we looked at
the coherent state.

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:30.580
And now, of course, when we
looked at the coherent state,

00:05:30.580 --> 00:05:34.660
we realize that coherent
states are maybe not

00:05:34.660 --> 00:05:37.520
as wonderful as I tried
to make you believe.

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:39.560
They have some nasty properties.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:43.540
And that is when you ask,
What is the probability?

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:47.580
The quasi-probability of the
coherent state would be beta.

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:49.410
Now, if you would
expect a delta function,

00:05:49.410 --> 00:05:52.200
because when you ask, What is
the probability of a momentum

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:53.277
state to be p naught?

00:05:53.277 --> 00:05:54.860
If you have a momentum
state p naught,

00:05:54.860 --> 00:05:57.180
it has a delta
function at p naught.

00:05:57.180 --> 00:05:59.230
But here, it's not
a delta function.

00:05:59.230 --> 00:06:04.510
It's a Gaussian of the
standard deviation.

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:07.210
I think the standard deviation
here is-- what is it,

00:06:07.210 --> 00:06:08.820
square root 1 over
square root 2?

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:12.090
Because the Gaussian has
usually 2 times sigma squared.

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:14.150
And since the
denominator is unity--

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:16.770
so the standard deviation
of 1 over square root 2.

00:06:16.770 --> 00:06:21.950
And that showed us that
the coherent states are not

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:22.540
orthogonal.

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:24.040
You have to be a
little bit careful.

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:26.340
It's not your
standard basis set.

00:06:26.340 --> 00:06:27.820
It's an overcomplete basis.

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:37.840
So therefore the
coherent state is not

00:06:37.840 --> 00:06:39.750
a delta function in
the causal probability.

00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:43.280
It's a little bit blurred
circle with an area

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:46.730
on the order of unity.

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:53.380
And you have some homework
assignment to look at it.

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:55.610
So in some way, how
you should look at

00:06:55.610 --> 00:07:02.320
it is that if you see some
quasi-probability distribution,

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.040
the distance from
the origin-- this

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:06.820
is the absolute value
of the electric field.

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:10.020
The phase here is
almost 45 degrees.

00:07:10.020 --> 00:07:11.605
But if you look at
this uncertainty,

00:07:11.605 --> 00:07:13.785
you would also say,
Well, the phase

00:07:13.785 --> 00:07:16.990
is uncertain to
within this angle.

00:07:16.990 --> 00:07:19.540
So you can pretty much
read the uncertainty

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:23.690
in the total electric field,
the uncertainty in the phase.

00:07:23.690 --> 00:07:25.150
You can read pretty
much everything

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:26.420
you want from this diagram.

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:34.800
Now, when we look at
a number state-- Well,

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:36.440
you often know in
quantum mechanics,

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:39.000
number and phase
are complimentary.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.040
If the number of
photons is fixed,

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:42.860
you know nothing
about the phase.

00:07:42.860 --> 00:07:46.580
And indeed the quasi-probability
of a number state is a ring.

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:47.530
It has no phase.

00:07:47.530 --> 00:07:51.268
It has completely random
phase over the 2 pi circle.

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:57.370
The energy is sharp
of a number state,

00:07:57.370 --> 00:08:01.120
since the energy is e squared.

00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:05.150
You may have expected
a delta function

00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:06.730
in the radial coordinate.

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:08.320
But what you get
is also something

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:09.630
blurred on the order of unity.

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:13.460
And I want to say something
about that in a second.

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:17.190
Finally, we discuss
the time dependence.

00:08:17.190 --> 00:08:19.580
And the time dependence
is very easy.

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:22.380
After all, we're dealing
with an harmonic oscillator.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:24.500
And in an harmonic
oscillator, if you

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:30.760
have a plane of x and p,
symmetric and anti-symmetric

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:33.500
combination of a and a
dagger, in this plane

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:36.289
in an harmonic oscillator,
the quantum state

00:08:36.289 --> 00:08:39.860
is just rotating circle,
a rotation with omega.

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:43.870
And indeed we showed that when
we apply the time evolution

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:46.990
operator-- and some of
you were right, of course,

00:08:46.990 --> 00:08:51.890
with a minus sign-- it moves
with e to the minus i omega t.

00:08:51.890 --> 00:08:59.780
And therefore everything
rotates in a clockwise way.

00:09:02.310 --> 00:09:11.540
Now, we discussed the operator
of the electric field.

00:09:11.540 --> 00:09:17.920
And in this
quasi-probability-- Sorry,

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.930
we discussed the operator
of the electric field.

00:09:20.930 --> 00:09:23.750
And I hope you remember
that in the analogy

00:09:23.750 --> 00:09:26.670
with the harmonic oscillator,
the electric field was

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:28.099
a minus a dagger.

00:09:28.099 --> 00:09:29.515
And this is the
momentum operator.

00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:36.910
In those quasi-probabilities--
and we will see more about it--

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:39.530
something which is
sharp in momentum

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:43.640
is a sliver parallel
to the x-axis.

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:48.320
So therefore, you can
regard the vertical axis,

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.630
which is the imaginary part of
alpha, as the momentum axis.

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:54.490
And you can regard this
as-- the horizontal axis--

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:56.270
as the x-axis.

00:09:56.270 --> 00:09:59.500
So therefore, since
momentum is electric field,

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.180
you always get
the electric field

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:03.890
by projecting onto
the vertical axis.

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:06.510
And if you project
this fuzzy ball,

00:10:06.510 --> 00:10:10.810
you get a value 0
with some uncertainty.

00:10:10.810 --> 00:10:12.960
And if this
quasi-probability starts

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:15.800
to rotate due to
the time evolution,

00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:20.790
we get an oscillating
electromagnetic field, almost

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:23.890
classical except
for that fuzziness.

00:10:32.870 --> 00:10:37.720
So that's where we
want to continue.

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:39.760
Any questions about that?

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:40.559
Yes?

00:10:40.559 --> 00:10:43.912
AUDIENCE: Why is there no
phase fuzziness in the E t?

00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:50.940
PROFESSOR: No phase fuzziness.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:52.820
There is a phrase fuzziness.

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:55.830
For instance, if you would
say the phase is determined

00:10:55.830 --> 00:10:58.650
by the 0 crossing, you don't
know exactly when the 0

00:10:58.650 --> 00:11:00.480
crossing happened,
and that corresponds

00:11:00.480 --> 00:11:03.870
to an uncertainty in the phase.

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:07.220
Trust me, everything
is in this diagram.

00:11:07.220 --> 00:11:10.490
Now, there are two things
we want to continue.

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:16.700
One is I want to show you
that the coherent state is

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:18.570
a minimum uncertainty state.

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:27.372
The product of delta
x delta p is just--

00:11:27.372 --> 00:11:29.380
is it h-bar or h-bar over two?

00:11:29.380 --> 00:11:31.370
One of the two.

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:33.370
So it's a minimum
uncertainty state.

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:36.500
And therefore, you can
never have a quantum state

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:39.260
which is less fuzzy
than the coherent state.

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:42.630
So this fuzziness here is
the intrinsic uncertainty

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:44.110
of quantum physics.

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:47.460
So that's what we
want to discuss today.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:51.150
But then we will
immediately start

00:11:51.150 --> 00:11:53.000
with non-classical states.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.140
And that is, well, if
this area is determined

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:58.970
by Heisenberg's
uncertainty relation, what

00:11:58.970 --> 00:12:02.650
can be maybe deform the
circle into an ellipse,

00:12:02.650 --> 00:12:04.910
and these are three
states of light.

00:12:04.910 --> 00:12:05.785
So that's an outlook.

00:12:05.785 --> 00:12:07.826
That's what you're going
to do in the second half

00:12:07.826 --> 00:12:08.410
of the class.

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:23.720
But before I do that, I
want to be a little bit more

00:12:23.720 --> 00:12:25.690
accurate about
quasi-probabilities.

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:37.830
And this is almost
like a disclaimer now.

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:50.980
Just to give you
the bigger picture.

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:53.900
What we want to achieve with
those quasi-probabilities,

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:57.300
we want to do what phase space
densities in classical physics.

00:12:57.300 --> 00:13:01.150
We have a coordinate which is
x, a coordinate which is p.

00:13:01.150 --> 00:13:04.510
And you can often describe
a classical system

00:13:04.510 --> 00:13:07.070
if you know the phase
space distribution,

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:09.650
if you know the probability
that a particle has

00:13:09.650 --> 00:13:12.280
position x and momentum p.

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:20.070
So all this is about
phase space densities.

00:13:26.740 --> 00:13:32.902
Probability of x and p.

00:13:32.902 --> 00:13:36.730
Of course, writing it down, you
immediately see the problem.

00:13:36.730 --> 00:13:40.490
In quantum mechanics, you cannot
measure x and p simultaneously.

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:43.440
These are non-commuting
variables.

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:50.860
So therefore, what happens is,
if you now define a phase space

00:13:50.860 --> 00:13:54.370
function, which is done in
quantum mechanics textbooks,

00:13:54.370 --> 00:13:58.050
you can actually do it
in three different ways.

00:13:58.050 --> 00:14:05.300
And the three different
ways are Q, P, and W.

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:07.740
The definition--
I don't want to go

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:10.190
through the mathematical
subtleties-- the definition

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:15.210
of those functions involves
the operator definition, a

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:19.970
and a dagger, or,
which is equivalent,

00:14:19.970 --> 00:14:21.930
the x and p operator.

00:14:25.080 --> 00:14:30.120
If you define something in units
of x and p or a and a dagger,

00:14:30.120 --> 00:14:33.120
you can have a product
which is fully symmetric i

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:39.220
in the ordering of x p, which
is anti-normal or normal.

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:41.990
So in other words,
the order matters.

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:47.850
And you have three choices.

00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:54.080
In an operator product, you can
have symmetric ordering, which

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:58.310
means not x p, but x p
plus p x, then it's over 2.

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:00.900
That's symmetric.

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:04.660
You can have an ordering
which is called normal

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:06.315
and one which is
called anti-normal.

00:15:14.430 --> 00:15:22.695
Ordering of operators in the
operator base definition.

00:15:33.930 --> 00:15:37.430
Of course, if you
have three choices,

00:15:37.430 --> 00:15:39.240
you would say, Which
one is the best?

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:40.840
Which one is the winner?

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:44.490
But the fact is all three
have their advantages

00:15:44.490 --> 00:15:45.240
and disadvantages.

00:15:55.520 --> 00:16:01.410
So they all have
pluses and minuses.

00:16:01.410 --> 00:16:06.630
The reason why I picked
for the course Q of alpha

00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:09.900
is that it's a real probability,
it's always positive.

00:16:15.060 --> 00:16:19.520
It is a diagonal matrix element
of a statistical operator,

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:21.160
and this has to be positive.

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:23.260
So it's a real probability.

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:30.100
The other guys, P of alpha,
can be positive or negative.

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:33.230
And also, W of alpha can
be positive or negative.

00:16:41.420 --> 00:16:44.540
So if you use a P
alpha distribution

00:16:44.540 --> 00:16:56.340
statistical operator, it
can be written like this.

00:16:56.340 --> 00:17:07.680
And as a result, the coherent
state is now not this Gaussian.

00:17:07.680 --> 00:17:09.579
It doesn't have this
Gaussian distribution

00:17:09.579 --> 00:17:11.099
as a course of probability.

00:17:11.099 --> 00:17:13.180
It's what you want--
what maybe some of you

00:17:13.180 --> 00:17:16.000
wanted to see-- oh, by the
way, it's a delta function.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.680
The probability of the
coherent state alpha

00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:24.520
has a delta function peak at
alpha, which is sort of nice.

00:17:24.520 --> 00:17:30.350
And the number state is not
a ring of a finite radius.

00:17:30.350 --> 00:17:32.600
I just mentioned to
you the number state.

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:35.800
You would naively expect
the energy is sharp.

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:38.080
The square root of the
energy's electric field,

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:39.970
shouldn't it be sharp?

00:17:39.970 --> 00:17:41.980
And indeed, it is sharp.

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:44.390
It's actually worse
than a delta function.

00:17:44.390 --> 00:17:46.125
It's a derivative
of a delta function.

00:17:51.390 --> 00:17:55.690
But at least here,
in the probability P,

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:59.470
which is also called
the Glauber-Sudarshan P

00:17:59.470 --> 00:18:05.890
representation, you
get the delta function,

00:18:05.890 --> 00:18:09.205
which may be very natural
for certain purposes.

00:18:09.205 --> 00:18:12.189
AUDIENCE: Since the [INAUDIBLE]
and you can express one

00:18:12.189 --> 00:18:15.300
in terms of the
other, is that unique?

00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:19.810
PROFESSOR: It is unique by
some symmetry choice here.

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:30.240
So that's the advantage
of it, that by-- I'm not

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:31.460
going into the mathematics.

00:18:31.460 --> 00:18:32.410
I'm not giving
you the definition

00:18:32.410 --> 00:18:33.618
but the way how it's defined.

00:18:33.618 --> 00:18:34.180
It's unique.

00:18:34.180 --> 00:18:35.760
It can be written in such a way.

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:38.220
And the way how the
quasi-probabilities

00:18:38.220 --> 00:18:42.100
P-- the P representation--
is defined,

00:18:42.100 --> 00:18:44.110
you get a delta function
at the coherent state.

00:18:46.770 --> 00:18:50.860
And finally, W stands
for Wigner distribution.

00:18:55.480 --> 00:19:01.570
And the Wigner distribution
is something you actually

00:19:01.570 --> 00:19:03.980
find in most quantum
mechanics textbooks.

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:07.300
The Q and P distribution are
more common in quantum optics.

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:10.490
But the Wigner distribution
has the advantage

00:19:10.490 --> 00:19:17.380
that the projection
on the x- and y-axes

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:26.950
are indeed psi of x
squared, psi of p squared.

00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:30.760
So you get actually the x
wave function and the p wave

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:32.580
function.

00:19:32.580 --> 00:19:35.950
So now, as a full
disclaimer, if you

00:19:35.950 --> 00:19:40.600
want the electric field, which
is the momentum of the harmonic

00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:44.680
oscillator, which is the
electromagnetic field, what you

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:49.030
really want to project is the
W function, because for the W

00:19:49.030 --> 00:19:51.250
function, the Wigner
function, the projection

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:53.060
is exactly the
momentum distribution

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:56.240
in the electric field.

00:19:56.240 --> 00:20:06.500
So the Wigner distribution is
closest to the classic phase

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:09.560
space distribution,
as close as you

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:13.030
come without
violating commutators.

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:20.600
But of course it
has a disadvantage

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:22.850
that it has negative values.

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:25.710
And try to explain to
your next neighbor what

00:20:25.710 --> 00:20:28.990
is a negative probability.

00:20:28.990 --> 00:20:34.500
Some people actually see
negative probabilities spring

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:36.420
out the non-classical character.

00:20:36.420 --> 00:20:38.990
And I know in our
field, in AMO physics,

00:20:38.990 --> 00:20:41.380
a few years ago, in
my lifetime, there

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:45.010
were really attempts to use
quantum state homography

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:48.950
and measure for the first time
a negative Wigner distribution

00:20:48.950 --> 00:20:50.530
and show that to the world.

00:20:50.530 --> 00:20:53.520
So that meant something
to a lot of people.

00:20:53.520 --> 00:21:00.300
Anyway, you can read about it
in quantum physics textbooks.

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:02.690
All I want you to know
is to know about it,

00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:05.947
but then also just relax.

00:21:05.947 --> 00:21:08.030
In the bigger picture, all
the three distributions

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:09.340
are the same.

00:21:09.340 --> 00:21:12.270
It's more sort of on the
level of whether something

00:21:12.270 --> 00:21:14.660
is a delta function
or has widths unity.

00:21:14.660 --> 00:21:17.630
So on the small
scale, it matters.

00:21:17.630 --> 00:21:20.450
But if you map out
something on a bigger scale,

00:21:20.450 --> 00:21:24.390
they are all related
to each other.

00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:26.830
And for the rest off
today and the next class,

00:21:26.830 --> 00:21:29.520
when I show you those phase
space distribution, when

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:33.240
I say I project onto
the vertical axis

00:21:33.240 --> 00:21:36.190
to get the electric
field, I'm not

00:21:36.190 --> 00:21:39.340
completely rigorous which
of the three functions

00:21:39.340 --> 00:21:40.280
I've really chosen.

00:21:43.687 --> 00:21:44.270
Any questions?

00:21:57.260 --> 00:21:57.760
OK.

00:22:00.670 --> 00:22:03.070
So I promised you--
and this is what

00:22:03.070 --> 00:22:07.300
we're going to do now is
we're want to understand

00:22:07.300 --> 00:22:10.723
in more depth the fluctuations.

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:19.550
And in particular,
I want to show you

00:22:19.550 --> 00:22:24.610
that coherent states are
minimum uncertainty states.

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:41.250
So by identifying the
vertical axis with p,

00:22:41.250 --> 00:22:46.230
the horizontal axis with
x, we immediately expect

00:22:46.230 --> 00:22:50.260
that we find a result related
the Heisenberg uncertainty

00:22:50.260 --> 00:22:55.480
principle, which says sit the
widths in P and the widths in Q

00:22:55.480 --> 00:22:59.780
has to be larger
than h-bar over 2.

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:10.930
And we are mainly talking with
light about the photon creation

00:23:10.930 --> 00:23:14.210
and annihilation operator.

00:23:14.210 --> 00:23:21.640
But, just as a reminder, the
momentum and position operator

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:28.906
are symmetric and
anti-symmetric combinations.

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:47.540
So let me just call
those [? prefecters ?]

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:51.843
Q naught and this one P naught.

00:23:59.100 --> 00:24:06.230
Well, we can then
immediately, by just

00:24:06.230 --> 00:24:11.190
using elementary
commutator, calculate

00:24:11.190 --> 00:24:17.276
what are the expectation values
in a coherent state for P,

00:24:17.276 --> 00:24:20.330
P squared, Q, and Q squared.

00:24:24.380 --> 00:24:38.550
For P, it is-- the P
operator is a dagger minus a.

00:24:38.550 --> 00:24:42.270
If we act with a on
alpha, we get alpha,

00:24:42.270 --> 00:24:43.880
because alpha-- the
coherent state--

00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:47.060
is an eigenstate of alpha.

00:24:47.060 --> 00:24:49.850
Now, with a dagger we act
on the left hand side.

00:24:49.850 --> 00:24:51.460
And we get alpha star.

00:24:59.450 --> 00:25:01.330
Well, with P squared
and Q squared,

00:25:01.330 --> 00:25:04.750
you have to use one
or two more steps

00:25:04.750 --> 00:25:06.550
to get rid of the products.

00:25:06.550 --> 00:25:10.350
But ultimately, you can
express space all that just

00:25:10.350 --> 00:25:17.400
in powers of alpha, alpha
squared, alpha star, and such.

00:25:17.400 --> 00:25:24.040
So what we want is
we want to find out

00:25:24.040 --> 00:25:32.210
what are the fluctuations delta
Q, delta P. Just as a reminder,

00:25:32.210 --> 00:25:40.190
delta Q squared is of course Q
squared average minus Q average

00:25:40.190 --> 00:25:41.010
squared.

00:25:41.010 --> 00:25:43.772
And Q squared
average and Q squared

00:25:43.772 --> 00:25:45.105
is what we have just calculated.

00:25:55.330 --> 00:25:58.370
Actually, let me leave it
in as a reminder for you--

00:25:58.370 --> 00:26:03.890
Q squared minus Q average
squared, the square root of it.

00:26:03.890 --> 00:26:11.990
And what we find is that it's
square root h-bar over 2 omega

00:26:11.990 --> 00:26:17.710
and, for delta P, it is square
root h-bar over omega 2.

00:26:17.710 --> 00:26:23.190
And what we verify, that
indeed, for a coherent state,

00:26:23.190 --> 00:26:26.635
the product of the 2 is
Heisenberg uncertainty limit.

00:26:31.110 --> 00:26:44.855
So therefore, coherent states
are minimum uncertainty states.

00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:02.560
And maybe, Colin, to
address your question,

00:27:02.560 --> 00:27:04.590
I could imagine that
coherent states were maybe

00:27:04.590 --> 00:27:07.650
invented by simply saying, We
have an harmonic oscillator

00:27:07.650 --> 00:27:08.200
data.

00:27:08.200 --> 00:27:12.480
We want to find the
minimum uncertainty

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:17.130
states for which the
uncertainty in x and p,

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:21.660
when expressed in natural
units, is the same.

00:27:21.660 --> 00:27:23.740
In other words,
the coherent state

00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:27.780
is the solution to the
following question.

00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:36.470
If you plot the
quasi-probability distribution,

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:40.980
you give yourself
an uncertainty area.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:49.060
One horizontal
uncertainty is delta Q.

00:27:49.060 --> 00:27:55.500
The vertical
uncertainty is delta P.

00:27:55.500 --> 00:28:00.570
And the minimum
uncertainty state

00:28:00.570 --> 00:28:05.080
means that the area of the
2 uncertainties, the area

00:28:05.080 --> 00:28:18.040
of the shaded region, delta P
times delta Q is h-bar over 2.

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:31.094
Or if I want to
rewrite that in-- Yes,

00:28:31.094 --> 00:28:37.210
in the real part of alpha
times the uncertainty

00:28:37.210 --> 00:28:41.810
in the imaginary part of alpha
for the quasi-probability,

00:28:41.810 --> 00:28:43.100
then this is 1/4.

00:28:57.650 --> 00:28:58.150
OK.

00:28:58.150 --> 00:29:04.460
So what we have learned
is that-- just one second.

00:29:04.460 --> 00:29:12.480
We have learned about one way
to characterize uncertainties--

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:16.660
the quantumness of the
electromagnetic field--

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:22.950
by looking at the uncertainties
in the x and p variable.

00:29:22.950 --> 00:29:26.230
And that led us to minimum
uncertainty states.

00:29:26.230 --> 00:29:28.830
Now, I want to now
introduce to you

00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:35.930
two other ways of characterizing
the uncertainty of quantum

00:29:35.930 --> 00:29:37.300
states of light.

00:29:37.300 --> 00:29:43.370
One is we can ask, What are
the fluctuations in the photon

00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:44.490
number?

00:29:44.490 --> 00:29:45.950
Right now, we have
asked, What are

00:29:45.950 --> 00:29:48.274
the fluctuations in
the electric field?

00:29:48.274 --> 00:29:49.690
But the next
question is, What are

00:29:49.690 --> 00:29:51.400
the fluctuations in
the photon number?

00:29:54.200 --> 00:29:56.490
Or we can ask, what
are fluctuations

00:29:56.490 --> 00:29:59.950
in the intensity when
we measure the intensity

00:29:59.950 --> 00:30:02.732
of the electromagnetic field?

00:30:02.732 --> 00:30:03.440
So let's do that.

00:30:08.890 --> 00:30:22.265
The fluctuations-- It
seems I've lost my lines.

00:30:34.260 --> 00:30:35.730
OK.

00:30:35.730 --> 00:30:41.950
So the fluctuations
of the intensity

00:30:41.950 --> 00:30:45.380
are usually expressed by the
second order temporal coherence

00:30:45.380 --> 00:30:47.039
function.

00:30:47.039 --> 00:30:48.580
That's what we want
to introduce now.

00:31:09.810 --> 00:31:21.550
Yes, this is the second
order temporal correlation

00:31:21.550 --> 00:31:23.570
or coherence function.

00:31:28.880 --> 00:31:30.950
What I'm always
encountering in this course

00:31:30.950 --> 00:31:33.720
is I would just like
to immediately tell you

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:37.110
how it is defined in terms
of a's and a daggers.

00:31:37.110 --> 00:31:37.950
It's simple.

00:31:37.950 --> 00:31:39.130
It's quantum mechanical.

00:31:39.130 --> 00:31:40.320
It's exact.

00:31:40.320 --> 00:31:46.190
But I always feel that if
you want to really appreciate

00:31:46.190 --> 00:31:49.560
the quantum character, you have
to know the classic description

00:31:49.560 --> 00:31:50.710
first.

00:31:50.710 --> 00:31:55.270
So I want to first tell you what
is the second order coherence

00:31:55.270 --> 00:31:57.540
function for
classical light, which

00:31:57.540 --> 00:31:59.690
has a classic description.

00:31:59.690 --> 00:32:03.394
And then you'll see
what is the difference

00:32:03.394 --> 00:32:04.560
for quantum states of light.

00:32:07.840 --> 00:32:12.040
So the classical
description is you

00:32:12.040 --> 00:32:14.785
measure the intensity of light.

00:32:14.785 --> 00:32:16.020
You're just sitting here.

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:18.870
You receive light
from a light bulb.

00:32:18.870 --> 00:32:21.180
You measure the
intensity at time t.

00:32:21.180 --> 00:32:27.620
You measure the intensity
at time tau later.

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:28.965
And then you form the product.

00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:37.730
And you normalize it by the
average intensity squared.

00:32:37.730 --> 00:32:41.580
So if tau equals 0,
it's nothing else

00:32:41.580 --> 00:32:45.830
than the intensity
squared average divided

00:32:45.830 --> 00:32:47.910
by the average of the
intensity squared.

00:33:00.100 --> 00:33:07.360
So this is the classical
definition, g2 of tau.

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:11.770
And I've left the
proof to the homework

00:33:11.770 --> 00:33:24.560
to show that the classical g2
of tau is always larger than 1.

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:29.000
But it's pretty much what
you show is for tau equal 0,

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.680
it means I squared
average is larger

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:35.770
than I average squared, which
is, of course, always the case.

00:33:35.770 --> 00:33:40.230
But you can show that this is
also the case for finite tau.

00:33:40.230 --> 00:33:48.150
So quantum mechanically, we will
see that the g2 function is not

00:33:48.150 --> 00:33:52.060
necessarily larger than 1,
it can be smaller than 1.

00:33:52.060 --> 00:33:53.700
And that's actually
an interesting--

00:33:53.700 --> 00:33:57.070
you can see-- litmus
test for the quantumness.

00:33:57.070 --> 00:34:02.770
If you generate states of the
electromagnetic field-- Fock

00:34:02.770 --> 00:34:05.560
states, photon number states--
we see that in a moment.

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:09.350
And they have a g2 of tau
which is smaller than 1.

00:34:09.350 --> 00:34:12.749
You know it is not
possible in any way

00:34:12.749 --> 00:34:18.900
to associate an intensity
of the electromagnetic field

00:34:18.900 --> 00:34:21.230
with that photon
state, because whenever

00:34:21.230 --> 00:34:24.600
you can associate a
classical intensity with it

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:28.409
and use a classical intensity
to calculate the second order

00:34:28.409 --> 00:34:30.210
correlation function,
you get something

00:34:30.210 --> 00:34:32.030
which is larger than 1.

00:34:32.030 --> 00:34:34.440
So often therefore
again, when people

00:34:34.440 --> 00:34:38.929
want to show we really have now
non-classical photon states,

00:34:38.929 --> 00:34:44.020
they show g2 of tau
is smaller than 1.

00:34:44.020 --> 00:34:46.469
This is similar to
what I said before when

00:34:46.469 --> 00:34:51.040
you want to show that you
have non-classical light,

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:53.780
you do quantum state
homography, measure the Wigner

00:34:53.780 --> 00:34:56.540
distribution, and show that
the Wigner distribution has

00:34:56.540 --> 00:34:58.360
negative quasi-probabilities.

00:34:58.360 --> 00:35:01.590
That's again something which
is classically not possible.

00:35:01.590 --> 00:35:06.407
It's only possible if you have
a truly non-classical state.

00:35:06.407 --> 00:35:08.365
AUDIENCE: So in the
definition of g2 classical,

00:35:08.365 --> 00:35:11.732
the expectation values would
need averaging over time, not

00:35:11.732 --> 00:35:15.797
over ensembles of I of t?

00:35:15.797 --> 00:35:16.380
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:21.240
You can average over ensembles.

00:35:21.240 --> 00:35:25.660
So you can have 1,000 light
bulbs, switch them all on,

00:35:25.660 --> 00:35:28.010
and then measure at
a certain time z.

00:35:28.010 --> 00:35:31.190
But what we assume here
is that the light bulb

00:35:31.190 --> 00:35:32.580
is on continuously.

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:34.490
So things don't
really depend on t.

00:35:38.620 --> 00:35:41.990
I've implicitly taken care of
it by defining the g2 function

00:35:41.990 --> 00:35:44.520
only of tau and
not of t and tau.

00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:48.560
You assume any time is the same,
because it's a distribution,

00:35:48.560 --> 00:35:51.530
it's this ensemble
in steady state.

00:35:51.530 --> 00:35:54.920
But it's sort of the same
story again and again.

00:35:54.920 --> 00:35:58.650
In classical physics, you can
determine an ensemble average

00:35:58.650 --> 00:36:01.640
by taking an ergotic
system and observing it

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:03.250
at many, many times.

00:36:03.250 --> 00:36:06.410
And then the idea is
that one system as time

00:36:06.410 --> 00:36:09.880
goes by will sample
all possible states.

00:36:09.880 --> 00:36:13.350
Or you can prepare many,
many identical systems

00:36:13.350 --> 00:36:17.239
and do more of what is
an ensemble average.

00:36:17.239 --> 00:36:18.780
So in other words,
you would actually

00:36:18.780 --> 00:36:21.740
think, if you switch on a
light bulb with a stable power

00:36:21.740 --> 00:36:24.310
supply, that the light
emitted by the light bulb

00:36:24.310 --> 00:36:29.570
will go through all possible
quantum states as time evolves.

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:31.580
And therefore, the
temporal average

00:36:31.580 --> 00:36:33.080
is equal to the
ensemble average.

00:36:55.380 --> 00:37:01.073
So how do we generalize
that to quantum mechanics?

00:37:04.360 --> 00:37:11.610
Well, one possibility
would be that-- OK.

00:37:11.610 --> 00:37:13.299
First of all, for
quantum mechanics,

00:37:13.299 --> 00:37:14.340
we have to use operators.

00:37:23.470 --> 00:37:31.910
And one choice would
be that, well, you

00:37:31.910 --> 00:37:37.420
say the intensity of
the electromagnetic wave

00:37:37.420 --> 00:37:40.600
is proportional to the
electric field squared.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:44.770
And you want to use the operator
for the electric field squared.

00:37:44.770 --> 00:37:48.090
Now, there is a little
bit of a problem,

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:51.340
because what we really
mean quantum mechanically

00:37:51.340 --> 00:37:55.790
by g2 of tau is we
measure the intensity now

00:37:55.790 --> 00:37:57.210
and a little bit later.

00:37:57.210 --> 00:38:01.520
But measuring the intensity
really means absorbing photons,

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:05.040
because the only way how you can
measure the intensity of light

00:38:05.040 --> 00:38:07.280
is with a photomultiplier.

00:38:07.280 --> 00:38:09.790
It makes click, the
photon is absorbed.

00:38:09.790 --> 00:38:14.280
And this is not fully described
by the electric field.

00:38:14.280 --> 00:38:17.240
Just assume you
have no photon, you

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:20.600
are in the zero-point state
of your harmonic oscillator,

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:24.760
and your E squared has
zero-point fluctuations.

00:38:24.760 --> 00:38:30.640
So what is more closely
related to an experiment how

00:38:30.640 --> 00:38:34.210
you measure the
correlation function is

00:38:34.210 --> 00:38:39.640
you want to look
at something else,

00:38:39.640 --> 00:38:55.180
namely at the probability
of absorbing 2 photons.

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:03.690
So you start with
an initial state.

00:39:07.140 --> 00:39:09.750
You annihilate 2 photons.

00:39:09.750 --> 00:39:12.570
And then you have a final state.

00:39:12.570 --> 00:39:15.220
But if you're only
interested in what

00:39:15.220 --> 00:39:17.080
is the probability you
want to characterize

00:39:17.080 --> 00:39:22.140
your initial state, you may want
to sum over all final state.

00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:23.890
And this is your
total probability

00:39:23.890 --> 00:39:28.250
that you can absorb 2 photons
out of an initial state.

00:39:28.250 --> 00:39:33.110
But since you're in sum
now over all final state,

00:39:33.110 --> 00:39:40.290
this turns into--
Now, I could put

00:39:40.290 --> 00:39:45.970
for you as in the final
state is a complete basis.

00:39:45.970 --> 00:39:47.405
But I can also take it out.

00:39:53.650 --> 00:39:56.520
So this is what we get.

00:39:56.520 --> 00:40:02.200
So this suggests
that experiments

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:07.630
where we look at two subsequent
clicks of a photomultiplier

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:10.960
where we determine the
photon correlation,

00:40:10.960 --> 00:40:17.090
that this is measuring a
correlation function, which,

00:40:17.090 --> 00:40:21.060
for quantum states of
light, should be defined

00:40:21.060 --> 00:40:27.000
as the expectation value of
a dagger, a dagger, a, a.

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:35.870
And now we have to normalize
by the probability squared

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:43.735
of absorbing 1 photon, which
is a dagger a expectation

00:40:43.735 --> 00:40:44.485
value squared.

00:40:48.940 --> 00:40:51.820
I just tried to be a
little bit too motivated.

00:40:51.820 --> 00:40:53.620
In many, many textbooks,
the discussion

00:40:53.620 --> 00:40:54.995
would start with
this expression.

00:40:54.995 --> 00:40:57.090
You ask, Where
does it come from?

00:40:57.090 --> 00:41:01.460
And you realize yes,
for some measurement

00:41:01.460 --> 00:41:03.980
with photomultipliers,
that's what you measure.

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:11.060
But I wanted to show you how
it is related to the intensity

00:41:11.060 --> 00:41:13.440
correlation function
defined classically.

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:14.246
Cody.

