00:41:28.750 --> 00:41:33.580
is I've swept here-- I
just wanted to give you

00:41:33.580 --> 00:41:36.720
the structure of the
operators and not

00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:39.250
get distracted by
discussing time.

00:41:39.250 --> 00:41:41.510
I've dropped the
time argument here.

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:52.550
But the fact is that as
long as we limit ourselves

00:41:52.550 --> 00:41:55.070
to a single mode of the
electromagnetic field,

00:41:55.070 --> 00:41:59.910
a single harmonic oscillator,
things are independent of tau.

00:41:59.910 --> 00:42:05.110
In other words, g2 of
tau equals g2 of 0,

00:42:05.110 --> 00:42:07.790
as long as we're dealing
with single mode light.

00:42:07.790 --> 00:42:11.480
You can actually say--
and that sort of tells you

00:42:11.480 --> 00:42:15.750
where the fluctuations
come-- if g2 of tau changes,

00:42:15.750 --> 00:42:18.530
it comes because you
have several modes

00:42:18.530 --> 00:42:21.990
of the electromagnetic field,
which, as a function of time,

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.820
constructively and
destructively interfere.

00:42:24.820 --> 00:42:27.790
But if you have a single
mode, in a single mode--

00:42:27.790 --> 00:42:29.590
and what is a single mode?

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:31.190
It's just a sine wave.

00:42:31.190 --> 00:42:33.330
And nothing happens
as a function of time.

00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:35.200
It's constant.

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:37.334
AUDIENCE: So both
modes go inside.

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:47.030
PROFESSOR: I'm squeezing a
textbook of quantum optics

00:42:47.030 --> 00:42:48.550
into two classes.

00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:52.170
And I want to give you the
