00:42:52.170 --> 00:42:56.550
What I've sort of mixed
up here deliberately

00:42:56.550 --> 00:42:59.830
is I've given you the classic
definition of the intensity

00:42:59.830 --> 00:43:04.150
correlation function, which is
the famous Hanbury Brown Twiss

00:43:04.150 --> 00:43:06.640
experiment, and
used correlations

00:43:06.640 --> 00:43:08.530
as a function of time.

00:43:08.530 --> 00:43:10.580
Then I've motivated
how this should

00:43:10.580 --> 00:43:13.520
be defined for quantum
states of light.

00:43:13.520 --> 00:43:16.730
But when I transitioned to
quantum states of light,

00:43:16.730 --> 00:43:21.290
I decided to deal with
only one mode of the light.

00:43:21.290 --> 00:43:24.840
We should now sum
over-- I should

00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:28.600
put double or triple
indices on all the alphas

00:43:28.600 --> 00:43:31.090
for polarization,
for spatial modes,

00:43:31.090 --> 00:43:34.600
for different frequencies,
and we sum over all of them.

00:43:34.600 --> 00:43:38.470
But instead what I did is
I wanted to just show you

00:43:38.470 --> 00:43:41.704
the simple case-- and I
think you will be thankful

00:43:41.704 --> 00:43:43.370
for that in your
homework, that you only

00:43:43.370 --> 00:43:45.010
have to deal with
the simple case--

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:47.410
that you only have to
look at a's and a daggers

00:43:47.410 --> 00:43:50.400
in the operator algebra
for single mode,

00:43:50.400 --> 00:43:52.700
for single harmonic oscillator.

00:43:52.700 --> 00:43:54.680
But what we lose,
so to speak here,

00:43:54.680 --> 00:43:57.530
is there is nothing
interesting going on in time.

00:43:57.530 --> 00:44:01.170
I've already told you that,
for a single mode, all

00:44:01.170 --> 00:44:04.630
of these quasi-probabilities,
they just rotate in a circle.

00:44:04.630 --> 00:44:07.160
So the time evolution
of the system

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:09.730
you're describing right
now is completely boring.

00:44:09.730 --> 00:44:11.340
It's really a rotation.

00:44:11.340 --> 00:44:13.577
And if you would rotate
your head at omega,

00:44:13.577 --> 00:44:14.410
nothing will happen.

00:44:14.410 --> 00:44:16.840
And this is exactly
what you see here.

00:44:16.840 --> 00:44:22.200
So you find everything you
want to for coherence time.

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:26.010
Coherence time is the time for
2 modes to get out of phase.

00:44:26.010 --> 00:44:29.560
But if you have 1 mode,
there is no coherence time.

00:44:29.560 --> 00:44:32.420
And when you find,
for classical light,

00:44:32.420 --> 00:44:37.880
that the g2 function has a peak
which decays with the time,

00:44:37.880 --> 00:44:41.030
it is the time for modes
to get out of phase.

00:44:41.030 --> 00:44:44.690
But in a single mode
picture, this is absent.

00:44:44.690 --> 00:44:48.600
Anyway, what is important now
for the discussion of quantum

00:44:48.600 --> 00:44:51.460
character of light
is really, we find

00:44:51.460 --> 00:44:52.820
that in a single mode picture.

00:44:52.820 --> 00:44:56.400
So I want to show you
now-- or at least give you

00:44:56.400 --> 00:44:57.910
the summary of
the results, which

00:44:57.910 --> 00:45:00.240
can be very easily derived,
because the math is very

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:02.860
simple of those
operators, that we are now

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:04.260
with that definition.

00:45:04.260 --> 00:45:08.340
We have g2 functions, which
are no longer following

00:45:08.340 --> 00:45:11.490
the classic constraint that
g2 has to be larger than 1.

00:45:11.490 --> 00:45:14.370
We find g2 functions
which are smaller than 1.

00:45:14.370 --> 00:45:17.110
And this sort of
tells us now where

00:45:17.110 --> 00:45:21.890
do we find the most
non-classical behavior,

00:45:21.890 --> 00:45:24.750
namely when g2 of tau
is as small as possible.

00:45:33.180 --> 00:45:34.810
OK.

00:45:34.810 --> 00:45:39.420
In your homework, you
will show immediately

00:45:39.420 --> 00:45:46.935
that the g2 function is
related to number fluctuations.

00:45:51.690 --> 00:45:55.745
It's related to an average
and an n-squared average.

00:46:00.570 --> 00:46:02.810
Let me just write that down.

00:46:02.810 --> 00:46:06.290
It's independent of tau.

00:46:06.290 --> 00:46:11.180
And the reason is we have
now limited ourselves

00:46:11.180 --> 00:46:14.460
to just one mode of the
electromagnetic field.

00:46:27.771 --> 00:46:28.757
Fano factor.

00:46:36.190 --> 00:46:37.305
Just give me one--

00:46:41.190 --> 00:46:45.660
OK So we are back
to-- We started

00:46:45.660 --> 00:46:47.670
with intensity fluctuations.

00:46:47.670 --> 00:46:50.170
But for a single mode of
the electromagnetic field,

00:46:50.170 --> 00:46:52.110
we are back to photon numbers.

00:46:52.110 --> 00:46:56.400
So what we are now expressing
with the g2 function

00:46:56.400 --> 00:47:00.805
are, in other words, just
fluctuations of photon numbers.

00:47:05.700 --> 00:47:08.760
I want to in a minute
draw you a table.

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:11.070
What are the fluctuations
in the photon number

00:47:11.070 --> 00:47:13.610
for the states we have
encountered-- the number

00:47:13.610 --> 00:47:16.430
state, the Fock state,
the coherent state,

00:47:16.430 --> 00:47:18.080
and the thermal state?

00:47:18.080 --> 00:47:25.710
And we want to characterize
those quantum states of light

00:47:25.710 --> 00:47:28.490
by the g2 function.

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:31.660
And actually, I can drop to
time argument or set it to 0.

00:47:36.500 --> 00:47:38.460
But then we first
make a reference

00:47:38.460 --> 00:47:43.460
that g2 can now
be smaller than 1.

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:48.600
So g2 for a single mode light
is nothing else than a function.

00:47:48.600 --> 00:47:51.700
When you know what is an
average and n squared average,

00:47:51.700 --> 00:47:54.300
you know your g2 function.

00:47:54.300 --> 00:47:57.950
There is another
quantity, which we often

00:47:57.950 --> 00:48:02.700
use to characterize the
fluctuations in the photon

00:48:02.700 --> 00:48:03.230
number.

00:48:03.230 --> 00:48:06.400
And this is called
the Fano factor.

00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:13.940
The Fano factor is-- wants
to compare the fluctuations.

00:48:13.940 --> 00:48:19.712
n square average minus
n average squared,

00:48:19.712 --> 00:48:20.836
these are the fluctuations.

00:48:24.280 --> 00:48:26.850
The classical
fluctuation-- well,

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:31.750
I say classical, classical
in the simplest case--

00:48:31.750 --> 00:48:33.533
are Poissonian fluctuations.

00:48:36.260 --> 00:48:39.880
So maybe we want to
normalize the fluctuations

00:48:39.880 --> 00:48:42.100
by Poissonian fluctuation.

00:48:42.100 --> 00:48:48.610
So for Poissonian statistics,
what I just wrote down

00:48:48.610 --> 00:48:49.450
would be 1.

00:48:58.570 --> 00:49:04.870
And well, if you
now subtract 1, we

00:49:04.870 --> 00:49:07.680
have the situation that
the final factor, which

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:10.470
is positive, is
super-Poissonian--

00:49:10.470 --> 00:49:12.430
more fluctuation
than Poissonian--

00:49:12.430 --> 00:49:15.150
and the negative final
factor is sub-Poissonian.

00:49:19.030 --> 00:49:24.670
So with those
definitions, we can now

00:49:24.670 --> 00:49:35.810
compare the different states
of light we have introduced.

00:49:39.480 --> 00:49:44.770
We started out with black-body
radiation, thermal radiation.

00:49:44.770 --> 00:49:49.320
We defined coherent states.

00:49:49.320 --> 00:49:53.150
And the harmonic oscillator
description naturally

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:55.560
gave us harmonic
oscillator eigenstates,

00:49:55.560 --> 00:49:59.540
the number of states,
or Fock states.

00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:03.050
So there are three ways
to characterize it.

00:50:03.050 --> 00:50:07.790
They are all useful.

00:50:07.790 --> 00:50:10.550
One is we can look at n squared.

00:50:10.550 --> 00:50:13.250
We can calculate
the Fano factor.

00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:15.730
Or we can calculate g2 of 0.

00:50:18.830 --> 00:50:26.030
For the coherent
state-- remember,

00:50:26.030 --> 00:50:28.600
the coherent state
is as close as we

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:31.180
can come quantum
mechanically to the ideal

00:50:31.180 --> 00:50:34.090
of a pure electromagnetic wave.

00:50:34.090 --> 00:50:37.930
It has a Fano factor of 0.

00:50:37.930 --> 00:50:42.280
This means it's Poissonian.

00:50:42.280 --> 00:50:46.970
The g2 function
is simply 1, which

00:50:46.970 --> 00:50:51.230
is the lowest classical limit.

00:50:51.230 --> 00:50:55.340
So those two tell you that a
coherent state is sometimes

00:50:55.340 --> 00:50:57.880
what you think-- what
comes out of a laser is

00:50:57.880 --> 00:51:01.060
an ideal electromagnetic
wave, which

00:51:01.060 --> 00:51:04.160
has no temporal fluctuations
in the intensity.

00:51:04.160 --> 00:51:06.660
Therefore, g2 is 1.

00:51:06.660 --> 00:51:10.930
And the photon number is
Poissonian distributed.

00:51:10.930 --> 00:51:16.440
And that means that n
squared is an average times 1

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:18.060
plus an average.

00:51:18.060 --> 00:51:19.720
We actually
discussed it earlier.

00:51:22.450 --> 00:51:25.890
The thermal state
is quite different.

00:51:25.890 --> 00:51:29.330
If you use-- kind
of pluck together

00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:33.715
the results we have obtained,
it has a Fano factor of n-bar.

00:51:38.310 --> 00:51:40.560
So this is super-Poissonian.

00:51:43.210 --> 00:51:45.440
If the occupation
number n is large,

00:51:45.440 --> 00:51:47.460
you have fluctuations
which are much,

00:51:47.460 --> 00:51:50.500
much larger than
Poissonian fluctuation.

00:51:50.500 --> 00:51:53.630
The g2 function is 2.

00:51:53.630 --> 00:51:56.040
It's sometimes
called thermal light.

00:51:56.040 --> 00:51:59.500
Chaotic light has
a g2 function of 2.

00:51:59.500 --> 00:52:03.790
Laser light or coherent state
has a g2 function of one.

00:52:03.790 --> 00:52:10.010
And n square average is
n-bar 1 plus 2 n-bar.

00:52:14.050 --> 00:52:14.550
OK.

00:52:14.550 --> 00:52:17.780
But now finally, maybe
the most interesting state

00:52:17.780 --> 00:52:20.620
from the perspective of
non-classical light--

00:52:20.620 --> 00:52:24.110
of quantum light-- is
the photon number state.

00:52:24.110 --> 00:52:28.890
Well, for the photon number
state, the number of photons

00:52:28.890 --> 00:52:31.520
is an eigenvalue.

00:52:31.520 --> 00:52:37.980
Therefore, n squared average
is n average squared.

00:52:37.980 --> 00:52:42.050
The Fano factor is minus 1.

00:52:42.050 --> 00:52:45.910
Sub-Poissonian distribution.

00:52:45.910 --> 00:52:50.990
And the g2 function, which
classically cannot go below 1,

00:52:50.990 --> 00:52:55.280
is now n minus 1 over n.

00:52:55.280 --> 00:52:57.600
It is smaller than 1.

00:52:57.600 --> 00:53:03.650
And you see immediately that
the biggest violation for g2

00:53:03.650 --> 00:53:13.780
is to go to minus 1 for the
case of a single photon state.

