00:55:36.770 --> 00:55:40.200
If you want to emphasize the
difference between quantum

00:55:40.200 --> 00:55:43.950
light and classic light,
where does it come from?

00:55:43.950 --> 00:55:46.600
Well, it comes from the
quantization of light.

00:55:46.600 --> 00:55:48.640
It comes from the
photon character.

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:51.480
It comes from the
effect that light is not

00:55:51.480 --> 00:55:56.390
a continuous stream of energy,
it comes quantized in photons.

00:55:56.390 --> 00:56:00.240
So the granularity of light
due to the photon character

00:56:00.240 --> 00:56:05.044
is, of course, most pronounced
for a single photon.

00:56:05.044 --> 00:56:08.150
For instance, when we
define the g2 function

00:56:08.150 --> 00:56:10.750
as a correlation of
detecting a photon

00:56:10.750 --> 00:56:13.110
and detecting
another photon, well,

00:56:13.110 --> 00:56:16.110
if you've only one photon,
you find one photon,

00:56:16.110 --> 00:56:19.460
and for the next photon, there
is no photon to be detected.

00:56:19.460 --> 00:56:23.220
So the probability of
detecting two photons is 0.

00:56:23.220 --> 00:56:26.410
And that only happens when you
go down to similar photons.

00:56:26.410 --> 00:56:31.210
So this is when
certain fluctuations

00:56:31.210 --> 00:56:37.470
are most pronounced,
because the energy is

00:56:37.470 --> 00:56:38.860
dependant on a singular photon.

00:56:41.370 --> 00:56:43.216
