00:57:08.752 --> 00:57:11.210
When you have a coherent state,
when you have a laser beam,

00:57:11.210 --> 00:57:12.790
you can put an attenuator.

00:57:12.790 --> 00:57:16.110
And your laser beam gets
weaker and weaker and weaker.

00:57:16.110 --> 00:57:17.840
But it stays a coherent state.

00:57:17.840 --> 00:57:20.490
And I will prove that
to you very soon.

00:57:20.490 --> 00:57:24.370
So you can now say that you
take your coherent state

00:57:24.370 --> 00:57:28.205
and you attenuate it down that
there is only one photon left.

00:57:28.205 --> 00:57:31.950
Is that a single photon state?

00:57:31.950 --> 00:57:33.480
The answer is no.

00:57:33.480 --> 00:57:35.990
It is an attenuated
coherent state.

00:57:35.990 --> 00:57:39.760
Coherent states, as I've just
shown you, are very classical.

00:57:39.760 --> 00:57:41.930
They've always
Poissonian distribution.

00:57:41.930 --> 00:57:43.980
They've always a
g2 function of 1.

00:57:43.980 --> 00:57:46.420
And attenuation is
not changing it.

00:57:46.420 --> 00:57:49.030
Attenuation is preserving that.

00:57:49.030 --> 00:57:52.730
So now I want to
show you explicitly

00:57:52.730 --> 00:57:58.100
why an attenuated coherent
state may have an average photon

00:57:58.100 --> 00:58:03.010
number of 1 but it shares
nothing else with a quantum

00:58:03.010 --> 00:58:06.270
state of 1 photon of
n equals 1 Fock state.

00:58:08.900 --> 00:58:16.770
So a coherent state with an
expectation value of 1 photon

00:58:16.770 --> 00:58:19.770
is not a single photon.

00:58:24.680 --> 00:58:33.640
And this can be, for
instance, expressed

00:58:33.640 --> 00:58:37.590
by looking what is
actually the probability,

00:58:37.590 --> 00:58:39.910
if you have such
a coherent state,

00:58:39.910 --> 00:58:44.270
to find 1, 2, or 3 photons.

00:58:44.270 --> 00:58:52.440
Well, the probability to find
0 photons-- no photon at all--

00:58:52.440 --> 00:58:54.550
is actually 1/3.

00:58:54.550 --> 00:59:00.740
So the probability to find 1
photon or to find 0 photons

00:59:00.740 --> 00:59:03.040
is the same.

00:59:03.040 --> 00:59:06.880
The probability to
find 2 photons is 0.18.

00:59:06.880 --> 00:59:09.360
So here you have a probability
of finding a photon

00:59:09.360 --> 00:59:12.490
and correlating it with
the next photon click.

00:59:12.490 --> 00:59:15.390
And you have even,
on first sight,

00:59:15.390 --> 00:59:25.690
a surprisingly large probability
to find 3 and 4 photons.

00:59:25.690 --> 00:59:30.810
So in 2 percent of the cases,
you will find 4 photons.

00:59:37.410 --> 00:59:43.930
Whereas in contrast, the Fock
state with quantum number n

00:59:43.930 --> 00:59:54.350
equals 1 is an eigenstate
of the number operator

00:59:54.350 --> 00:59:58.440
beta with eigenvalue n equals 1.

01:00:02.980 --> 01:00:08.580
So that tells you, if you
want to get n equals 1,

01:00:08.580 --> 01:00:11.000
if you want to get a
single photon state,

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:18.060
you cannot just use a strong
laser beam or a strong light

01:00:18.060 --> 01:00:19.840
source and attenuate it.

01:00:19.840 --> 01:00:24.920
You have to work with something
which genuinely creates only 1

01:00:24.920 --> 01:00:30.090
photon without any ambiguity,
without any fluctuations,

01:00:30.090 --> 01:00:34.840
without any possibility
of creating 2 photons.

01:00:34.840 --> 01:00:38.920
And I would actually say
over the last 10 or 15 years,

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.750
the creation of
single photons has

01:00:41.750 --> 01:00:44.790
been sort of a small
cottage industry,

01:00:44.790 --> 01:00:50.600
because single photons are often
needed for protocols in quantum

01:00:50.600 --> 01:00:57.530
computation-- for experiments
which really require accurate

01:00:57.530 --> 01:00:59.800
quantum state
preparation of light--

01:00:59.800 --> 01:01:03.050
and in particular,
non-classical light.

01:01:03.050 --> 01:01:09.970
But of course, there are ways
how you can get single photons.

01:01:09.970 --> 01:01:13.540
And this is, well, you
start with single atoms.

01:01:13.540 --> 01:01:17.910
If you have a single atom
in the excited state,

01:01:17.910 --> 01:01:19.590
it can emit only one photon.

01:01:34.930 --> 01:01:44.450
So in other words,
you cannot-- Usually,

01:01:44.450 --> 01:01:47.410
we don't have the tools to
prepare a single photon--

01:01:47.410 --> 01:01:50.530
to take a single photon
out of many, many photons--

01:01:50.530 --> 01:01:52.570
and store it separately.

01:01:52.570 --> 01:01:56.530
But what we can control
is single atoms.

01:01:56.530 --> 01:01:58.620
We can prepare single atoms.

01:01:58.620 --> 01:02:01.450
And then we can make
sure that single atoms

01:02:01.450 --> 01:02:02.900
create single photons.

01:02:02.900 --> 01:02:06.870
It's a little bit a way that
we cannot control the bullets

01:02:06.870 --> 01:02:07.820
which are fired.

01:02:07.820 --> 01:02:09.380
But we can control the guns.

01:02:09.380 --> 01:02:13.190
And we make sure that each gun
can emit exactly one bullet.

01:02:13.190 --> 01:02:14.910
So that's a way
how we can create

01:02:14.910 --> 01:02:16.916
non-classical states of light.

01:02:23.370 --> 01:02:24.690
Yes.

01:02:24.690 --> 01:02:33.738
So let's now look for
those single photons

01:02:33.738 --> 01:02:36.015
at the quasi-probability
distribution.

01:02:40.650 --> 01:02:45.580
So we obtain the
quasi-probability distribution

01:02:45.580 --> 01:02:50.880
by taking the
single photon state

01:02:50.880 --> 01:02:53.040
and projecting it
on a coherent state.

01:02:56.320 --> 01:02:59.790
You remember-- it's higher
up in the notes-- what

01:02:59.790 --> 01:03:03.540
the coherent state alpha
is in the Fock state basis,

01:03:03.540 --> 01:03:04.750
in a number basis.

01:03:04.750 --> 01:03:07.660
And so we're just
picking out n equals 1.

01:03:07.660 --> 01:03:11.365
And this was nothing
else than alpha

01:03:11.365 --> 01:03:15.790
squared times e to the
minus alpha squared.

01:03:15.790 --> 01:03:21.080
So therefore, in these
diagrams with the real part

01:03:21.080 --> 01:03:28.650
and imaginary part, if I
plot the quasi-probability

01:03:28.650 --> 01:03:35.700
distribution, we get a ring.

01:03:35.700 --> 01:03:40.650
The ring immediately tells us
that there is no phase defined.

01:03:40.650 --> 01:03:42.830
All the phases are
equally probable.

01:03:45.520 --> 01:03:47.800
And that also
means, if you don't

01:03:47.800 --> 01:03:53.550
have a phase, the average value
of the electric field this 0.

01:04:20.320 --> 01:04:27.020
Since the equation
of single photons

01:04:27.020 --> 01:04:30.630
is essential for studying
non-classical light,

01:04:30.630 --> 01:04:35.760
but also since it's a very
active frontier of our field--

01:04:35.760 --> 01:04:37.630
actually, one of the
leaders in this field

01:04:37.630 --> 01:04:40.320
is Professor Vladan
Vuletic here at MIT--

01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:43.160
let me at least give
you a taste of how

01:04:43.160 --> 01:04:46.990
to create single photons.

01:04:49.850 --> 01:04:54.500
I already gave you
the major ingredient.

01:04:54.500 --> 01:04:59.270
Namely, it's about-- it
involves single atoms.

01:04:59.270 --> 01:05:03.200
But it's a little bit
more demanding like that.

01:05:03.200 --> 01:05:06.630
So you want to take
1 atom home or 1 ion.

01:05:06.630 --> 01:05:11.310
But the problem is if the
atom or ion emits a light,

01:05:11.310 --> 01:05:14.690
it can emit the light
into all directions.

01:05:14.690 --> 01:05:18.310
And therefore, you have a
single photon afterwards.

01:05:18.310 --> 01:05:22.350
But you have many, many
different spacial modes.

01:05:22.350 --> 01:05:26.730
And in any given mode, it
will not have a single photon.

01:05:26.730 --> 01:05:33.420
So therefore, what you have
to add to the single atom

01:05:33.420 --> 01:05:36.790
or single ion is-- you
have to put it in a cavity.

01:05:49.030 --> 01:05:54.000
And then, in the limit of a
very, very high finesse cavity,

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:57.560
the probability will
be very, very high

01:05:57.560 --> 01:06:00.990
that your photon is emitted
into the mode of the cavity

01:06:00.990 --> 01:06:05.030
and it is not emitted
perpendicular into other modes.

01:06:05.030 --> 01:06:08.380
But that itself is
not yet sufficient,

01:06:08.380 --> 01:06:10.560
because you have
a single photon,

01:06:10.560 --> 01:06:14.520
but you also want to know when
does the single photon arrive.

01:06:14.520 --> 01:06:16.070
You want to do experiments.

01:06:16.070 --> 01:06:17.870
You want single
photons on demand.

01:06:21.580 --> 01:06:34.140
And so one option is that
you prepare your atoms

01:06:34.140 --> 01:06:36.970
in the ground state.

01:06:36.970 --> 01:06:43.630
You take a pi pulse, which,
with 100 percent probability,

01:06:43.630 --> 01:06:46.700
excites the atom to
the excited state.

01:06:50.310 --> 01:06:53.790
And then within an
actual lifetime,

01:06:53.790 --> 01:06:57.330
or maybe even in
resonator-enhanced inverse

01:06:57.330 --> 01:07:02.000
natural line widths, the
single photon is emitted.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:04.790
So therefore, you
pump the system

01:07:04.790 --> 01:07:07.730
and then you know within
the next few nanoseconds

01:07:07.730 --> 01:07:10.720
your cavity mode will
have a single photon.

01:07:25.110 --> 01:07:37.010
The problem here is
that you're dealing--

01:07:37.010 --> 01:07:43.250
You have to prepare single
atoms, which is difficult.

01:07:43.250 --> 01:07:46.290
You have to couple them
to a high finesse cavity.

01:07:46.290 --> 01:07:50.410
There is technically
another approach,

01:07:50.410 --> 01:07:53.235
where you use many atoms.

01:07:53.235 --> 01:07:54.610
So you could say
that many atoms,

01:07:54.610 --> 01:07:56.380
you no longer have a single gun.

01:07:56.380 --> 01:07:59.720
So therefore, you can
get several photons.

01:07:59.720 --> 01:08:05.310
But the singleness in photons
comes because the photons

01:08:05.310 --> 01:08:08.390
are now heralded--
they are announced.

01:08:08.390 --> 01:08:10.890
And the idea is the following.

01:08:10.890 --> 01:08:16.240
If you start with the state 1,
and you have an excited state,

01:08:16.240 --> 01:08:17.344
and you have a pump pulse.

01:08:20.130 --> 01:08:24.000
Now, if you have many atoms, you
have a much higher efficiency

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:25.930
of pumping atoms comes
to the excited state,

01:08:25.930 --> 01:08:29.490
because if you have n atoms,
it's n times more efficient.

01:08:29.490 --> 01:08:32.720
But now you take the
following situation.

01:08:32.720 --> 01:08:36.899
You wait until there
is a Raman transition--

01:08:36.899 --> 01:08:48.100
until you detect the photon
for Raman transition,

01:08:48.100 --> 01:08:53.939
where the excited state
decays to the state 2.

01:08:53.939 --> 01:09:00.810
At this moment, you know I
have now 1 atom in state 2.

01:09:03.510 --> 01:09:05.470
So in other words,
you're not starting

01:09:05.470 --> 01:09:08.840
with single atoms, which is
sometimes more demanding.

01:09:08.840 --> 01:09:10.840
How can you prepare the system?

01:09:10.840 --> 01:09:15.340
It has other disadvantages
that n atoms have.

01:09:18.149 --> 01:09:20.569
I'm not sure if I should
mention it, but with n atoms,

01:09:20.569 --> 01:09:23.740
they have a super-radiant
factor n with n atoms.

01:09:23.740 --> 01:09:27.099
You can get an n-times
enhancement of emission

01:09:27.099 --> 01:09:27.890
into a single mode.

01:09:27.890 --> 01:09:30.170
So there are real,
massive advantages

01:09:30.170 --> 01:09:32.220
in working with many atoms.

01:09:32.220 --> 01:09:36.220
But now you know that
one atom is in state 2

01:09:36.220 --> 01:09:38.990
when you detect
the first photon.

01:09:38.990 --> 01:09:44.790
And then you have the same
situation which we had above.

01:09:44.790 --> 01:09:50.210
You can now take your
system-- let me just

01:09:50.210 --> 01:09:51.990
redraw the level diagram.

01:09:51.990 --> 01:09:56.230
Excited state, state 1, state 2.

01:09:56.230 --> 01:10:01.810
You know now that you
have 1 single atom here.

01:10:01.810 --> 01:10:05.800
And by using a laser
pulse, you can excite it

01:10:05.800 --> 01:10:07.740
to the excited state.

01:10:07.740 --> 01:10:16.070
And then you observe
the single photon 2.

01:10:20.290 --> 01:10:24.250
So in other words,
the observation

01:10:24.250 --> 01:10:31.770
off the first photon
tells you that your system

01:10:31.770 --> 01:10:35.120
is prepared with
1 atom in state 2.

01:10:35.120 --> 01:10:37.970
And then you can get
a single photon out

01:10:37.970 --> 01:10:41.530
of it, which is the photon
for the inverse Raman

01:10:41.530 --> 01:10:45.249
transition when you pump
the system back to state 1.

01:10:45.249 --> 01:10:46.665
AUDIENCE: Doesn't
this rely on you

01:10:46.665 --> 01:10:52.848
being able to reliably prepare
a single atom in another quantum

01:10:52.848 --> 01:10:55.318
state?

01:10:55.318 --> 01:10:57.294
Won't there always
be some uncertainty

01:10:57.294 --> 01:10:59.764
as to how many atoms you
can prepare in one sitting?

01:11:06.674 --> 01:11:08.340
PROFESSOR: There are
some uncertainties.

01:11:08.340 --> 01:11:10.850
And what you're
saying is correct.

01:11:10.850 --> 01:11:14.070
We don't have perfect
single photon sources.

01:11:14.070 --> 01:11:19.520
And people characterize the
fidelity of the single photon

01:11:19.520 --> 01:11:20.150
source.

01:11:20.150 --> 01:11:26.750
For instance, if you detect the
single photon, you would say,

01:11:26.750 --> 01:11:30.460
Now my system is ready to
emit a single photon triggered

01:11:30.460 --> 01:11:31.752
by this pump pulse.

01:11:31.752 --> 01:11:33.335
And if you can get
now a single photon

01:11:33.335 --> 01:11:37.821
in 90 percent of the cases,
you publish a wonderful paper,

01:11:37.821 --> 01:11:39.820
because you've set a new
record for the fidelity

01:11:39.820 --> 01:11:41.490
of a single photon source.

01:11:41.490 --> 01:11:43.820
So people are really
struggling with some

01:11:43.820 --> 01:11:45.460
of those uncertainties.

01:11:45.460 --> 01:11:49.770
But to involve, for
instance, three levels

01:11:49.770 --> 01:11:52.690
is sort of an advantage,
because you're not

01:11:52.690 --> 01:11:56.290
limited by the preparation of
a single atom, for instance.

01:11:56.290 --> 01:11:57.540
You can have many atoms.

01:11:57.540 --> 01:11:59.260
The atoms are always there.

01:11:59.260 --> 01:12:02.810
And the moment one atom
is prepared in state 2,

01:12:02.810 --> 01:12:06.360
this atom announces itself
with a single photon.

01:12:06.360 --> 01:12:11.360
So it takes a lot of uncertainty
out that the system says,

01:12:11.360 --> 01:12:13.420
with the first
photon, I'm ready now.

01:12:13.420 --> 01:12:15.120
I can emit a single photon.

01:12:15.120 --> 01:12:17.270
And then you get
your single photon.

01:12:17.270 --> 01:12:19.930
Then you can gate
your whole experiment

01:12:19.930 --> 01:12:23.680
to a time following the
detection of the first photon.

01:12:23.680 --> 01:12:26.594
And for your gated
time afterwards, you

01:12:26.594 --> 01:12:28.010
have a very, very
high probability

01:12:28.010 --> 01:12:31.140
of finding this photon.

01:12:31.140 --> 01:12:34.590
Or if you want, you can now
do experiments with 2 photons.

01:12:34.590 --> 01:12:38.720
If you keep this laser on and
pump the atom immediately back,

01:12:38.720 --> 01:12:40.990
you have actually a
single photon here,

01:12:40.990 --> 01:12:42.550
followed by a
single photon here.

01:12:42.550 --> 01:12:44.370
It's sort of click clack.

01:12:44.370 --> 01:12:46.790
And now you can do
correlations between two

01:12:46.790 --> 01:12:49.720
different single
photon states and such.

01:12:49.720 --> 01:12:52.021
It's a very rich
frontier of our field.

01:12:52.021 --> 01:12:53.104
You have another question?

01:12:53.104 --> 01:12:54.078
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:12:54.078 --> 01:12:57.487
Is this also within a cavity
now, like the single photon

01:12:57.487 --> 01:12:58.950
[? reflection ?]
in the first test?

01:12:58.950 --> 01:12:59.685
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:12:59.685 --> 01:13:04.290
Actually, these photons--
the wavy lines--

01:13:04.290 --> 01:13:06.290
are emitted spontaneously.

01:13:06.290 --> 01:13:09.800
Spontaneous emission,
pretty much by definition,

01:13:09.800 --> 01:13:12.170
goes into all possible
spatial modes.

01:13:12.170 --> 01:13:15.245
And the only way to control the
spatial mode is with a cavity.

01:13:18.520 --> 01:13:20.690
What I don't want
to go into details--

01:13:20.690 --> 01:13:23.170
but those who have an
understanding of that--

01:13:23.170 --> 01:13:24.250
is the following.

01:13:24.250 --> 01:13:31.060
If you n atoms and you prepare
one atom here in state 2,

01:13:31.060 --> 01:13:34.990
you do not know which of
your n atoms is prepared.

01:13:34.990 --> 01:13:40.250
So you have n indistinguishable
possibilities.

01:13:40.250 --> 01:13:42.740
And if you have n
indistinguishable probabilities

01:13:42.740 --> 01:13:46.840
which atom you have prepared,
the emission of the photon

01:13:46.840 --> 01:13:49.490
back is n times enhanced.

01:13:49.490 --> 01:13:53.030
So therefore, you
have actually a system

01:13:53.030 --> 01:13:57.690
which has an n times stronger
coupling to the cavity.

01:13:57.690 --> 01:14:02.820
So having n atoms makes
it much, much easier

01:14:02.820 --> 01:14:04.900
to construct a high
finesse cavity.

01:14:04.900 --> 01:14:07.850
You get this super
radiance increase

01:14:07.850 --> 01:14:11.270
of the strong coupling for free.

01:14:11.270 --> 01:14:16.280
And this is why there are
many reasons why you do not

01:14:16.280 --> 01:14:19.250
want to work with the
single ion or a single atom.

01:14:19.250 --> 01:14:20.160
It's possible.

01:14:20.160 --> 01:14:21.940
For very fundamental
experiments,

01:14:21.940 --> 01:14:23.920
people have shown
that it can be done.

01:14:23.920 --> 01:14:27.550
But technologically,
it's much easier and much

01:14:27.550 --> 01:14:30.030
more robust to work
with many atoms.

01:14:30.030 --> 01:14:32.370
But then you need
the many atoms have

01:14:32.370 --> 01:14:38.034
to tell you when 1 atom
is prepared to emit now

01:14:38.034 --> 01:14:38.700
a single photon.

01:14:43.200 --> 01:14:46.510
If you're interested
in this subject,

01:14:46.510 --> 01:14:50.060
talk to the students
in [INAUDIBLE] school.

01:14:50.060 --> 01:14:52.467
They're really the
world experts in that.

01:15:06.861 --> 01:15:07.360
OK.

01:15:07.360 --> 01:15:11.510
Finally, we're not really
getting to squeeze light.

01:15:11.510 --> 01:15:13.840
We start with squeezing
the light tomorrow.

01:15:16.360 --> 01:15:20.620
The last thing in
this major section

01:15:20.620 --> 01:15:33.860
is the famous Hanbury
Brown Twiss experiment.

01:15:38.150 --> 01:15:43.390
This was a landmark
experiment done in the 1950s.

01:15:43.390 --> 01:15:47.520
And it was the first
experiment which

01:15:47.520 --> 01:15:52.640
really looked at g2 functions
correlations, which one could

01:15:52.640 --> 01:15:55.490
say was the beginning
of quantum optics

01:15:55.490 --> 01:16:00.820
and modern experiments
with light.

01:16:00.820 --> 01:16:03.630
Probably until then, light was
just an electromagnetic wave

01:16:03.630 --> 01:16:05.190
people regarded as boring.

01:16:05.190 --> 01:16:07.890
But by measuring
now correlations,

01:16:07.890 --> 01:16:12.080
people realize that it's an
interesting object to study.

01:16:12.080 --> 01:16:18.990
I want to just go
over the basic scheme.

01:16:18.990 --> 01:16:21.600
You will look at it
a little bit more

01:16:21.600 --> 01:16:24.370
closely in your
homework assignment.

01:16:24.370 --> 01:16:27.720
So the idea behind an Hanbury
Brown Twiss experiment

01:16:27.720 --> 01:16:31.870
is that you have a
light source and you

01:16:31.870 --> 01:16:35.230
want to characterize it.

01:16:45.020 --> 01:16:48.635
So the light source emits light.

01:16:51.240 --> 01:16:54.790
And now, this is important.

01:16:54.790 --> 01:16:57.390
Whenever you want
to detect 2 photons,

01:16:57.390 --> 01:16:59.710
you want to figure out
it's 1 photon followed

01:16:59.710 --> 01:17:02.550
by another photon.

01:17:02.550 --> 01:17:05.280
Technically, you cannot do
it with a photomultiplier,

01:17:05.280 --> 01:17:09.610
because when a photomultiplier
clicks, it needs many,

01:17:09.610 --> 01:17:12.460
many nanoseconds for the
photomultiplier to read out

01:17:12.460 --> 01:17:16.070
the signal and recover to
recharge up its electrodes

01:17:16.070 --> 01:17:18.400
and be ready to detect
the next photon.

01:17:18.400 --> 01:17:21.560
So therefore, when you
want to find click click--

01:17:21.560 --> 01:17:24.650
double clicks in the
stream of light--

01:17:24.650 --> 01:17:27.170
you have to involve
a beam splitter

01:17:27.170 --> 01:17:28.610
and involve two photodetectors.

01:17:31.760 --> 01:17:34.150
Sure, you now need an
adequate description.

01:17:34.150 --> 01:17:36.250
But in principle,
you can now find

01:17:36.250 --> 01:17:39.980
2 photons which are only
a few picoseconds apart,

01:17:39.980 --> 01:17:47.220
because the first photon is
observed by the first detector,

01:17:47.220 --> 01:17:49.220
and the second
photon is detected

01:17:49.220 --> 01:17:51.209
by the second detector.

01:17:51.209 --> 01:17:53.500
Sure, you would say, What
happens if you're in the beam

01:17:53.500 --> 01:17:55.760
splitter, both photons
go to detector one?

01:17:55.760 --> 01:17:57.200
Well, that's tough luck.

01:17:57.200 --> 01:18:00.820
You take 1 chance in
2 that the 2 photons

01:18:00.820 --> 01:18:02.570
go to the 2 different detectors.

01:18:02.570 --> 01:18:06.730
But the beam splitter has to
be part of your experiment,

01:18:06.730 --> 01:18:08.800
has to become part
of your description.

01:18:08.800 --> 01:18:12.860
And this is what you do
in homework number one.

01:18:12.860 --> 01:18:20.400
So what we are asking here when
we measure the g2 function.

01:18:20.400 --> 01:18:23.540
Let's assume that tau equals 0.

01:18:23.540 --> 01:18:29.730
We are reading out a signal.

01:18:29.730 --> 01:18:32.835
And what we are using is
a coincidence detector.

01:18:37.560 --> 01:18:40.110
We are looking that in a
very small temporal window,

01:18:40.110 --> 01:18:43.330
2 photons are detected
simultaneously.

01:18:43.330 --> 01:18:45.360
Well, this is the
quantum version.

01:18:45.360 --> 01:18:48.190
The classical version
is the g2 function

01:18:48.190 --> 01:18:51.400
is the product of the
intensity at time t times

01:18:51.400 --> 01:18:54.880
the product of the intensity
at time t plus tau.

01:18:54.880 --> 01:18:57.780
So what you would do
here in this circuit,

01:18:57.780 --> 01:19:00.280
you would take the signal
from this detector, the signal

01:19:00.280 --> 01:19:02.450
from that, and multiply the two.

01:19:02.450 --> 01:19:06.480
This is how you determine I
of t times I of t plus tau.

01:19:11.820 --> 01:19:14.490
So whether you do it
in the classical domain

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:19.820
or whether you do it
in the quantum domain,

01:19:19.820 --> 01:19:23.050
this is the way how
you experimentally

01:19:23.050 --> 01:19:28.930
measure the second order
correlation function.

01:19:35.140 --> 01:19:41.100
In the classic limit, you
don't have to worry about it.

01:19:41.100 --> 01:19:44.450
The classical limit is always
a limit of high intensity.

01:19:44.450 --> 01:19:48.020
So at any given time, you
have a ton of photons.

01:19:48.020 --> 01:19:51.245
And then, at beam splitter,
half of the photons go left,

01:19:51.245 --> 01:19:52.640
half of the photons go right.

01:19:52.640 --> 01:19:54.370
You have an equal splitting.

01:19:54.370 --> 01:19:56.540
You have exactly
half the intensity

01:19:56.540 --> 01:20:00.750
in the left arm and the right
arm after the beam splitter.

01:20:00.750 --> 01:20:04.150
So there is no problem at
all with the quantization,

01:20:04.150 --> 01:20:06.640
because this is the
classical limit.

01:20:06.640 --> 01:20:10.340
So classically you
can say-- actually,

01:20:10.340 --> 01:20:13.390
I shouldn't say photon, I
should actually say intensity.

01:20:13.390 --> 01:20:16.240
The intensity splits equally.

01:20:24.530 --> 01:20:28.100
And if you do the measurement
with the coincidence detector,

01:20:28.100 --> 01:20:32.180
you find the difference
between the g2 function,

01:20:32.180 --> 01:20:34.010
which I discussed earlier.

01:20:34.010 --> 01:20:38.540
That the g2 function is 1 for
coherent light or laser light,

01:20:38.540 --> 01:20:41.475
and the g2 function is
2 for thermal light.

01:20:47.070 --> 01:20:50.110
That's actually the only
way how you can distinguish

01:20:50.110 --> 01:20:52.900
a light bulb from a laser beam.

01:20:52.900 --> 01:20:55.930
If you put a light bulb into
a cavity or couple the light

01:20:55.930 --> 01:20:58.320
from a light bulb into
a fiber, the light

01:20:58.320 --> 01:21:01.120
becomes spatially a single mode.

01:21:01.120 --> 01:21:03.120
If you put a very
narrow spectral filter

01:21:03.120 --> 01:21:06.410
or Fabry-Perot cavity,
the light becomes

01:21:06.410 --> 01:21:09.000
single mode in frequency domain.

01:21:09.000 --> 01:21:12.450
So when you take a light bulb
and spatially and spectrally

01:21:12.450 --> 01:21:17.140
filter it that it is single
mode, in terms of the mode,

01:21:17.140 --> 01:21:20.630
it is single mode as
a single mode laser.

01:21:20.630 --> 01:21:22.305
But it is the
correlation experimental

01:21:22.305 --> 01:21:25.900
which shows you that you
started with a thermal source.

01:21:25.900 --> 01:21:29.470
It has a g2 function of 2, and
you can never get rid of it,

01:21:29.470 --> 01:21:31.690
whereas the laser beam
has a g2 function of 1.

01:21:34.200 --> 01:21:34.850
OK.

01:21:34.850 --> 01:21:37.220
So this is the
classical version.

01:21:37.220 --> 01:21:39.970
In the quantum version,
especially when

01:21:39.970 --> 01:21:48.300
we have a single
photon, the photon

01:21:48.300 --> 01:21:52.660
can go to only one detector.

01:21:55.660 --> 01:21:59.800
And that means, for this
extreme case of a single photon,

01:21:59.800 --> 01:22:03.380
the g2 function is 0.

01:22:03.380 --> 01:22:07.810
Anyway, you will look at
those situations in more

01:22:07.810 --> 01:22:11.670
detail in you
