01:22:52.930 --> 01:22:56.655
And once this photon is
detected, we have vacuum,

01:22:56.655 --> 01:22:59.340
we have no photon left.

01:22:59.340 --> 01:23:06.450
So what may be confusing
here is, on first sight,

01:23:06.450 --> 01:23:09.770
is that the way how the
experiment is done and has been

01:23:09.770 --> 01:23:13.880
historically done, it's
not done we Fock states.

01:23:13.880 --> 01:23:16.780
It's done with the light
source in a continuous stream

01:23:16.780 --> 01:23:18.220
of photons.

01:23:18.220 --> 01:23:19.820
So Hanbury Brown
Twiss experiment,

01:23:19.820 --> 01:23:24.030
he looked at in
light bulb, or he

01:23:24.030 --> 01:23:26.900
looked at star light and such,
and determined the intensity

01:23:26.900 --> 01:23:27.760
correlation.

01:23:27.760 --> 01:23:29.800
He couldn't do the
experiment with lasers,

01:23:29.800 --> 01:23:31.660
but now we would
with a laser beam.

01:23:31.660 --> 01:23:34.000
And we find that g2 is 1.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:37.200
But in those
situations, we actually

01:23:37.200 --> 01:23:42.646
do not have the way-- we
have actually a beam, which

01:23:42.646 --> 01:23:45.180
is a stream of photons.

01:23:45.180 --> 01:23:48.190
And this requires a little
bit different description.

01:23:48.190 --> 01:23:52.210
In other words, when I
have a coherent state,

01:23:52.210 --> 01:23:55.790
a laser beam is
always replenishing

01:23:55.790 --> 01:23:56.740
the coherent state.

01:23:56.740 --> 01:23:59.570
The laser beam preserves
the electric field,

01:23:59.570 --> 01:24:03.220
whereas, strictly speaking,
the way how I described it

01:24:03.220 --> 01:24:06.370
for pedagogical reasons is
you have a cavity, which

01:24:06.370 --> 01:24:09.520
is filled with a
coherent state alpha.

01:24:09.520 --> 01:24:12.010
And then you start
analyzing that.

01:24:12.010 --> 01:24:16.080
But in other words,
what we have focused

01:24:16.080 --> 01:24:18.890
in the simple description
is that we have a quantum

01:24:18.890 --> 01:24:21.630
state which is prepared--
it's a closed system.

01:24:21.630 --> 01:24:24.090
And now we do our detection.

01:24:24.090 --> 01:24:26.940
The experiment how
it is done is often

01:24:26.940 --> 01:24:30.920
done as in an open system,
where you couple the system

01:24:30.920 --> 01:24:33.580
to a light source,
which is always

01:24:33.580 --> 01:24:36.080
replenishing your experiment.

01:24:36.080 --> 01:24:39.250
So to be careful, especially
with a single photon.

01:24:39.250 --> 01:24:41.490
I think, in essence,
the experiment

01:24:41.490 --> 01:24:44.090
would be done with a
single photon light source.

01:24:44.090 --> 01:24:45.890
But the single
photon light source

01:24:45.890 --> 01:24:48.370
has a high repetition rate.

01:24:48.370 --> 01:24:50.880
I showed you how to
generate single photons.

01:24:50.880 --> 01:24:53.430
You have an heralded
single photon.

01:24:53.430 --> 01:24:55.710
You know the single
photon comes now.

01:24:55.710 --> 01:24:57.110
You do the experiment.

01:24:57.110 --> 01:25:00.160
And then you repeat it again.

01:25:00.160 --> 01:25:01.730
And then what you
have is you only

01:25:01.730 --> 01:25:05.580
look at one single
photon bunch at a time.

01:25:05.580 --> 01:25:09.040
And then you find indeed, that
during that temporal window,

01:25:09.040 --> 01:25:11.210
you will never find
a second photon.

01:25:11.210 --> 01:25:13.650
So this may happen
in a few nanoseconds.

01:25:13.650 --> 01:25:18.100
Then you wait a microsecond,
and the next photon arrives.

01:25:18.100 --> 01:25:22.930
Of course, if you would now
describe your light source,

01:25:22.930 --> 01:25:26.980
what you is the g2 of tau,
and tau is a microsecond,

01:25:26.980 --> 01:25:30.360
and the microsecond is the time
between the first single photon

01:25:30.360 --> 01:25:33.000
burst and the next
single photon burst,

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:36.380
now you will find that
your g2 function is not 0.

01:25:36.380 --> 01:25:39.230
But this is then related
to the repetition

01:25:39.230 --> 01:25:42.560
rate of a single photon and not
to the single photon itself.

01:25:42.560 --> 01:25:44.810
I think you've got the taste.

